<ul class='children'>
   <li class="comment byuser comment-author-admin bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-4302">
  	

     <div id="comment-4302" >
	 
	 <div class="comment-metaLeft">
			<img src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/841d461f2528ab5b584954869f80136a?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2F61a58ec1c1fba116f8424035089b7c71%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' alt='' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />			</div>
			<div class="commentRight">
			<div class="commentBullet"></div>
				 <span><strong><a href='2007/01' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>rechosen</a></strong> </span>November 8, 2010 at 19:43 				
				  <div class="text"><p>There is a method, but whether you'd call it simple is up to you :). You can use a so-called ProxyCommand to make remote1 forward the ssh connection to remote2. Here's an example:</p>
<p>scp -o 'ProxyCommand ssh user1@remote1 nc remote2 22' filetocopy user2@remote2:/repository/somefile.war</p>
<p>And a little bit of explanation: this will only work when using OpenSSH and when remote1 has netcat installed. The command first connects to remote1 and executes the nc command there, which opens a connection to port 22 (the default SSH port) of remote2. Then your homepc uses the remote nc connection to connect to remote2 and copy the file there. Hope this helps.</p>
<p>Rechosen</p>
 </div>
				   			<div class="reply">
					 <a class='comment-reply-link' href='http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/ssh-and-scp-howto-tips-tricks?replytocom=4302#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-4302", "4302", "respond", "1")'>Reply</a>				  </div>
			</div>
	 
      
     </div>
</li>
